        "leonardo-lesson": {
            "id": "leonardo-lesson",
            "summary": "Leonardo teaches them to observe before drawing",
            "text": "Leonardo hands them each charcoal and paper. 'Before you draw, you must observe. Most people look but do not see. They draw what they think a thing looks like, not what it actually looks like.'\n\nHe places an apple on the table. 'Draw this.'\n\n{{BOTH_NAMES}} sketch quickly‚Äîa simple apple shape.\n\n'Now look again,' Leonardo instructs. 'Where does the light hit? Where are the shadows? Is the color uniform? See that slight bruise? That stem's curve? The reflection on the skin?'\n\nThey look more carefully. The apple isn't just round‚Äîit has subtle bulges, dimples, variations in color. They try again, slower this time.\n\n'Better!' Leonardo nods. 'Now here is the secret: draw what you see, not what you know. Your brain says apple is red and round. Your eyes see something much more complex. Trust your eyes.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}}'s second drawing is remarkably better. 'It takes patience,' {{PLAYER1_HE_SHE}} realizes.\n\n'Art always takes patience. Genius is patience‚Äîpatience to observe, patience to practice, patience to improve. There are no shortcuts.'",
