            "summary": "Botticelli shows them how Renaissance artists made paint from nature",
            "text": "Botticelli leads them to a table covered with mortars, pestles, shells, and jars filled with colorful substances.\n\n'Every color has a story,' he explains. 'This blue‚Äîultramarine‚Äîis made from lapis lazuli stones brought from Afghanistan, across thousands of miles. It costs more than gold. That's why we use it for the most important parts: the Virgin Mary's robe, the sky of paradise.'\n\nHe shows them other pigments. 'Red from crushed beetles. Yellow from saffron flowers or toxic arsenic minerals. Green from copper, which turns your fingers blue. White from lead, which slowly poisons you.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} looks concerned. 'Art is dangerous?'\n\n'Everything has a cost. But look‚Äî' He mixes egg yolk with a pigment, creating a smooth, glowing paint. 'Tempera. Egg binds the color and makes it glow. Oil is even better‚Äîit dries slowly, so you can blend and adjust. The medium changes everything.'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} tries mixing colors. Blue and yellow make green! But not the green {{PLAYER2_HE_SHE}} expected‚Äîmixing is more complex than it seems.",
