            "text": "'Why do you paint gods and goddesses?' {{PLAYER2_NAME}} asks. 'Did people really believe in them?'\n\n'Not exactly,' Botticelli says thoughtfully. 'The ancient myths are stories‚Äîbut stories that carry truth. Venus is not just a goddess; she is beauty itself. Mars is not just a god; he is the spirit of war. By painting them, I paint ideas that words cannot capture.'\n\nHe points to Primavera, his painting of spring. 'Look‚Äîthe three Graces dancing. They represent beauty, charm, and joy. Zephyr the wind chases a nymph who transforms into Flora, goddess of flowers. It's about nature's renewal, the triumph of life over winter.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} sees it now‚Äîthe painting isn't just pretty figures. It's telling a story about change, growth, the eternal return of spring.\n\n'Myths are humanity's first attempts to understand the world,' Botticelli continues. 'The sun crossing the sky became Apollo's chariot. The seasons became Persephone's journey. Before science, we had stories. And those stories still have power.'",
